header.gameNote: SEC TOURNAMENT AT NORTH LITTLE ROCK AR

article.description: Candace Parker's second double-double in as many games led Tennessee past Georgia on Saturday -- and into the SEC final against LSU.
article.headline: Tennessee, LSU to clash in SEC final
article.linkText: Parker's double-double leads Tennessee into SEC final
article.story:
NORTH LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Finally, a competitive game at
the women's SEC tournament.

And quite a prelude to the main event: Tennessee vs. LSU.

Candace Parker had 26 points and 12 rebounds to help the No. 8
Lady Vols pull away for an 89-79 win over No. 12 Georgia in the
semifinals Saturday night. Tennessee led 74-70 late in a
back-and-forth second half before going on an 8-0 run to secure its
17th appearance in the SEC title game.

Tennessee and LSU will play for the championship for the third
time in four years. LSU won in 2003 in North Little Rock, and the
Lady Vols took the title a season ago. The third-ranked Lady Tigers
won the regular-season matchup 72-69 at Tennessee.

"I think we're a better basketball team now than when we played
them," Lady Vols coach Pat Summitt said. "I feel good that we can
go inside against them."

Tye'sha Fluker added 19 points, and Shanna Zolman had 16 for
Tennessee, which was tested in the first game of the tournament
decided by fewer than 15 points. The Lady Vols (27-4) finally
pulled away with an impressive late stretch. Nicky Anosike made a
pair of free throws to make it 76-70, and Zolman followed a Georgia
turnover with a 3-pointer.

After another Georgia turnover, Parker was fouled with 4:09
remaining. She made one of two free throws, Tennessee rebounded the
miss, and Parker's reverse layup pushed the lead to 12.

Tennessee outrebounded Georgia 40-22.

"If you can control the boards, you usually have a great deal
of influence on how many possessions you get, how many
opportunities you get from that," Summitt said. "And I thought we
got a lot of opportunities."

Tennessee needed its rebounding advantage because the Lady Vols
turned over the ball 18 times against Georgia's pressure. The Lady
Bulldogs started 1-of-8 from the field and fell behind 16-5. They
trailed only 34-32 at halftime and the teams exchanged leads early
in the second.

"I thought that we were able to come back and almost get even
at the half encouraged us," Georgia coach Andy Landers said.

Georgia (21-8) made one more run late in the second. The Lady
Bulldogs had the possession down 85-79, but lost it on a jump ball
with 1:18 to play. Georgia then forced a shot clock violation, but
Tasha Humphrey's 3-pointer rimmed out.

"Once we settled down, everyone knew what we were in and we
were able to close out and finish the game," Parker said.

Sherill Baker led Georgia with 20 points and Humphrey added 18.

Parker, the SEC freshman of the year, went 9-of-12 from the
field. The 6-foot-4 forward was also Tennessee's primary
ball-handler against the press in the second half. She had five
turnovers but earned praise from her coach.

"Obviously Candace wanted the ball in her hands," Summitt
said. "She's a player that can see over people as well as go
around people."

Zolman made four 3-pointers for a season total of 82, breaking
Kara Lawson's school record of 79. She also had seven assists.
Anosike added 11 points and 11 rebounds.

Tennessee was 25-of-32 from the free throw line and Georgia was
20-of-21.

The Lady Vols haven't been their dominant selves this season,
losing to two unranked teams in one season for the first time since
the women's ranking started in 1976. Point guard Alexis Hornbuckle
was lost last month with a broken wrist.

But now, Tennessee is off to play for its 12th SEC tournament
title.

"It's just a matter of everyone stepping up and taking
responsibility and ownership on the offensive end," Summitt said.
"We executed very well."
